<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900919-0034</DOCNO><DOCID>900919-0034.</DOCID><HL>   Former CIA Agent Clines   Convicted of 4 Tax Charges</HL><DATE>09/19/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B10</SO><CO>   TAXES MDEST LATAM</CO><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)</IN><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)</GV><LP>   BALTIMORE -- A former CIA agent who procured arms as partof the secret Iran-Contra network supporting the Nicaraguanrebels was convicted of four tax charges.   Thomas Clines was found guilty yesterday by a jury infederal court in Baltimore of making false statements on taxreturns to hide his arms-dealing profits in the Iran-Contraaffair. The jury deliberated for about three hours beforeconvicting Mr. Clines on all four counts in the indictment.</LP><TEXT>   Mr. Clines, whom prosecutors had portrayed as a centralfigure in the Contra arms deals, is scheduled to be sentencedOct. 31. He faces a maximum prison term of 16 years and asmuch as $1 million in fines.   His lawyer attempted unsuccessfully during the 10-daytrial to portray her client's tax return misstatements andomissions as minor and at worst, negligent, not criminal.</TEXT></DOC>